The different types of texts, various styles and the peculiarities of written and oral expression are treated. The course is divided into theoretical and practical topics. The participants will acquire basic knowledge about stylistics, they will also analyse, revise and create texts that have different stylistic requirements.
Following topics will be discussed during seminars.
1. What is the subject of stylistics? What is style? Text types and genres.
2. Stylistic variation: marked usage vs unmarked. What can vary and why?
3. Style and norm: can there be mistakes of style that are not defined by context?
4. Lexicogrammatical choices 1: the stylistic value of grammatical forms and constructions.
5. Lexicogrammatical choices 2: the stylistic value of lexical units.
6. Functional usage and style.
7. Checking pupils' written assignments from stylistic point of view: what is a mistake and how can it be fixed?Objectives/eesmärkid:  To teach the students how to produce and understand texts in various situations, also how to see the importance and the role of the language in their activities.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  The student see the differences between different sublanguages and  functional styles; use the main sources of practical language planning (dictionaries, handbooks, websites, databases etc). The student will get an overview of stylistic variation in texts and the reasons behind it. The student will be able to point out stylistically marked usage and comment on its compatibility with the context of the communication act at hand. The student will be able to compile texts that take into account the stylistic requirements of particular situations and contexts.
